ffers a new way of understanding minority social experience. Drawing on gender studies and psychoanalysis, as well as critical legal and race studies, Gutiérrez-Jones's approach to the law and legal discourse reveals the high stakes involved when concepts of social justice are fought out in the home, in the workplace and in the streets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexMexican American authorsxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aAmerican literaturezUnited StatesxTheory, etcxMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturezUnited StatesxTheory, etc.xMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aLaw and literaturexSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aLaw and literaturexSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aLaw and literaturexSocial aspects. 0aMexican Americans in literature. 0aMexican AmericansxHistoriography. 0aMexican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aMexican AmericansxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh  aamerican law.  aamerican legal system.  achicanas.  achicano history.  achicanos.  acourt system.  acriminality.  acritical legal studies.  acritical race studies.  acultural studies.  agender studies.  ahispanic studies.  ahistorical amnesia.  alatin american history.  alatinos in american society and culture series.  alegal institutions.  alegal objectivity.  alegal system.  alegality.  aminority social experience.  amourning.  apopular culture.  aprison system.  apsychoanalysis.  aracial bias.  aracial discrimination.  asocial justice.  aunited states of america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008579440uhttps://doi.org/10.152